Phase 1 — Config Server

 Add dependencies: spring-cloud-config-server
 Annotate main class with @EnableConfigServer
 Set server.port=8888 in application.properties
 Choose config storage: local filesystem (simplest to start)
 Set spring.cloud.config.server.native.search-locations=classpath:/configs
 Set spring.profiles.active=native
 Create folder src/main/resources/configs/
 Inside that folder, create user-service.properties (put server.port=8081 in it for now)
 Run Config Server, hit http://localhost:8888/user-service/default — you should see JSON back
 ✅ Config Server is working


Phase 2 — Service Discovery (Eureka)

 Add dependencies: spring-cloud-starter-netflix-eureka-server
 Annotate main class with @EnableEurekaServer
 Set server.port=8761
 Add these in application.properties:

  eureka.client.register-with-eureka=false
  eureka.client.fetch-registry=false

 Run it, open http://localhost:8761 — Eureka dashboard should load
 Now go to User Service and make it register with Eureka:

Add dependency: spring-cloud-starter-netflix-eureka-client
Add spring.application.name=user-service
Add eureka.client.service-url.defaultZone=http://localhost:8761/eureka


 Run User Service, refresh Eureka dashboard — USER-SERVICE should appear in the list
 ✅ Service Discovery is working


Phase 3 — Config Server Integration (User Service reads from Config Server)

 In User Service, add dependency: spring-cloud-starter-config
 Rename application.properties → bootstrap.properties (or use spring.config.import if Spring Boot 2.4+)
 Add these in User Service config file:

  spring.application.name=user-service
  spring.cloud.config.uri=http://localhost:8888

 Remove hardcoded server.port from User Service — it should now come from Config Server's user-service.properties
 Restart Config Server first, then User Service
 Confirm User Service starts on port 8081 (pulled from Config Server)
 ✅ User Service is reading config from Config Server


Phase 4 — API Gateway

 Add dependencies: spring-cloud-starter-gateway, spring-cloud-starter-netflix-eureka-client
 Set server.port=8080
 Set spring.application.name=api-gateway
 Register Gateway with Eureka (same config as User Service above)
 Add route for User Service in application.yml:

yaml  spring:
    cloud:
      gateway:
        routes:
          - id: user-service
            uri: lb://user-service
            predicates:
              - Path=/api/users/**

 lb:// means load-balanced — Gateway asks Eureka for the address automatically
 Start everything in this order: Config → Eureka → User Service → Gateway
 Hit http://localhost:8080/api/users/health — should reach your User Service controller
 ✅ API Gateway routing is working


Startup Order (always follow this)
1. Config Server    (8888)
2. Eureka           (8761)
3. User Service     (8081)
4. API Gateway      (8080)

When You Get Stuck
Most common failures and where to look:
SymptomLikely causeUser Service won't startConfig Server not running yetService not showing in EurekaMissing eureka.client.service-url.defaultZoneGateway returns 503Service not registered in Eureka yet, wait 30sConfig not loadingWrong spring.application.name — must match filename in /configs/bootstrap.properties ignoredMissing spring-cloud-starter-bootstrap dependency

That's everything. Work through it top to bottom and only come back here if something in the error logs makes no sense. Good luck.
